# Rocket.new — Parallel Agent Workflow

> When a project has 2+ independent issues, fix them simultaneously in separate Cursor windows.
> Sequential fixing of independent problems is wasted time.

---

## When to Use Parallel Workflow

**Use it when**: Two issues exist that touch completely different files.

**Do NOT use it when**: Issues are in the same files or one fix depends on the other.

```
✅ PARALLEL — safe:
  - Auth broken + Stripe webhook broken (different files entirely)
  - RLS missing on table A + TypeScript errors in components
  - Deployment failure + missing email feature

❌ SEQUENTIAL — required:
  - Auth broken + dashboard not loading (dashboard may depend on auth fix)
  - RLS missing + data not loading (data issue may resolve after RLS fix)
  - middleware fix + protected route fix (middleware affects all routes)
```

---

## The Parallel Workflow Protocol

### Step 1 — After `/audit-codebase`, identify independent issues

From the audit report, group findings into buckets:
```
Bucket A: [Issues touching auth/middleware/session]
Bucket B: [Issues touching database/RLS/migrations]
Bucket C: [Issues touching Stripe/payments/webhooks]
Bucket D: [Issues touching deployment/env vars/Netlify]
```

Issues in different buckets can run in parallel. Issues in the same bucket must run sequentially.

### Step 2 — Open separate Cursor windows

```
Window 1: Fix Bucket A issues
  - Fresh chat
  - Open only auth-related files
  - Use /fix-auth command
  - Reference only: @middleware.ts @lib/supabase/ @app/auth/

Window 2: Fix Bucket B issues (simultaneously)
  - Fresh chat
  - Open only database-related files
  - Use /fix-database command
  - Reference only: @supabase/migrations/ @app/api/
```

Each window has its own focused context. They do not interfere with each other.

### Step 3 — Context isolation (critical)

Each parallel window must be scoped to its bucket ONLY.

```
Window 1 prompt opening:
"Rocket.new Next.js project. Working ONLY on auth issues.
Files in scope: @middleware.ts @lib/supabase/server.ts @app/auth/callback/route.ts
Do NOT touch anything outside these files."

Window 2 prompt opening:
"Rocket.new Next.js project. Working ONLY on database/RLS issues.
Files in scope: @supabase/migrations/ @app/api/
Do NOT touch anything outside these files."
```

### Step 4 — Merge in dependency order

When both windows complete their fixes:
1. Review Window 2 diff first (database layer — no dependencies)
2. Review Window 1 diff second (auth layer — may have DB dependency)
3. Run `/review-diff` on each before accepting
4. Apply fixes bottom-up: database → auth → UI

---

## Maximum Parallel Windows

**2 windows**: Always safe for any project
**3 windows**: Safe when all 3 buckets are fully independent
**4+ windows**: Only for very large projects with clearly isolated modules

Do not exceed 3 windows — review bottleneck becomes the constraint, not agent speed.

---

## The Speed Multiplier

A project with 3 independent issues fixed sequentially: ~90 minutes
A project with 3 independent issues fixed in parallel: ~35 minutes (limited by slowest fix + review time)

The constraint is no longer "how fast can the agent work" — it's "how fast can you review diffs."
Parallel workflow makes diff review the skill that matters most.

---

## CRITICAL — REPEATED AT BOTTOM

- **Parallel only for independent issues** — never for dependent fixes
- **Each window gets scoped context** — never share context between parallel windows
- **Review in dependency order** — bottom layer first, UI layer last
- **Run `/review-diff` on each window's output** before accepting any changes

---

## GIT WORKTREES — The Professional Parallel Approach

Opening multiple Cursor windows works but has a problem: files on disk are shared.
Both windows see the same `lib/` folder. One agent can overwrite the other's changes.

Git worktrees solve this completely — each agent gets its own isolated file system:

```bash
# Setup: create isolated branches for each parallel task
git worktree add ../[project]-auth-fix auth-fix
git worktree add ../[project]-db-fix db-fix

# Open each folder in a separate Cursor window
# Agent 1 works in ../[project]-auth-fix — completely isolated
# Agent 2 works in ../[project]-db-fix — completely isolated
# Zero file conflicts possible

# When both are done, merge:
git checkout main
git merge auth-fix
git merge db-fix

# Clean up
git worktree remove ../[project]-auth-fix
git worktree remove ../[project]-db-fix
git branch -d auth-fix db-fix
```

**When to use worktrees vs multiple windows:**

| Situation | Use |
|---|---|
| Agents touch different files, quick task | Multiple windows (simpler) |
| Agents might touch overlapping files | Git worktrees (safe) |
| Large feature, multiple days | Git worktrees (professional) |
| Team working in parallel | Git worktrees (mandatory) |

